+# Exploration 002 Summary
+
+## Goal
+
+Resolve the Step-4 ambiguity in `Delayed-Threshold Itinerary` by splitting it
+honestly or discarding it.
+
+## What I Tried
+
+- Re-read the original Step-2 itinerary clauses.
+- Tested whether the early delayed-trigger part and the late transfer part can
+  be separated on the same frozen window and threshold language.
+- Compared that split against `F_DT`, `F_SS`, and `F_SL`.
+
+## Outcome
+
+- `[INFERRED]` `pre-trigger delay filter` is definable on the frozen early
+  threshold language and cleanly separates hostile `F_DT` from friendly
+  `F_SS` / `F_SL`, but it is only a narrow admission filter and is discarded as
+  `not useful for the target theorem or counterexample question`.
+- `[INFERRED]` `next-stage transfer-start filter` cannot remove the
+  `F_SL(rho)` ambiguity without changing the late event language, so it is
+  discarded as `not well-defined`.
+
+## Key Takeaway
+
+The itinerary route does not survive the repair pass.
+The real bottleneck was exact late-stage event-trace rigidity, not leakage.
+
+## Leads Worth Pursuing
+
+- Carry forward only the algebraic/template and leakage candidates.
+- Treat the behavior screen as closed unless a later step earns a genuinely
+  same-currency late-stage gate.
+
+## Unexpected Findings
+
+- The low-leakage friendly family is exactly what makes the discard honest:
+  it proves the ambiguity is late-stage event language, not spectator
+  bookkeeping.
+
+## Computations Worth Doing Later
+
+- None for this branch unless a later chain explicitly reopens late-stage event
+  language from scratch.
